      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Correlation with MSRP\n",
        "\n",
        "The table above shows how strongly each variable is linearly related to MSRP. Correlation values range from **-1 to 1**:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Values closer to **1** → strong positive relationship  \n",
        "- Values closer to **-1** → strong negative relationship  \n",
        "- Values near **0** → weak or no relationship  \n",
        "\n",
        "### Key Insights\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Engine_HP (0.66)** has the strongest positive correlation with MSRP  \n",
        "  → Cars with higher horsepower tend to be significantly more expensive\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Engine_Cylinders (0.54)** also shows a strong positive relationship  \n",
        "  → More cylinders are associated with higher-priced vehicles\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Year (0.21)** has a moderate positive relationship  \n",
        "  → Newer cars tend to cost more\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Driven_Wheels (rear wheel drive) (0.16)** and **Vehicle_Size (0.12)**  \n",
        "  → Slight positive impact on price\n",
        "\n",
        "### Negative Relationships\n",
        "\n",
        "- **city_mpg (-0.16)** and **highway_MPG (-0.17)**  \n",
        "  → More fuel-efficient cars tend to be cheaper (likely because high-performance cars consume more fuel)\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Number_of_Doors (-0.14)**  \n",
        "  → Slight negative relationship, possibly reflecting that sportier (and more expensive) cars often have fewer doors\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Driven_Wheels_front wheel drive (-0.24)**  \n",
        "  → Front-wheel-drive cars tend to be less expensive compared to others\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Popularity (-0.05)** and **Driven_Wheels_four wheel drive (-0.03)**  \n",
        "  → Very weak relationships with MSRP\n",
        "\n",
        "### Overall Conclusion\n",
        "\n",
        "The correlation analysis shows that **engine-related variables (horsepower and cylinders)** are the strongest predictors of MSRP. However, no single variable has a perfect correlation, which indicates that **multiple factors must be combined** to build a strong predictive model."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "-P_2pWkeqh8T"
      }
    },
