        "## Log Model Feature Selection\n",
        "\n",
        "The output **\"Log model feature: Engine_HP\"** means that *Engine_HP* was selected as the variable to be used in the logarithmic regression model.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why is this check needed?\n",
        "\n",
        "Log transformations (log(x)) can **only be applied to positive values**. If a variable contains:\n",
        "- 0 → log(0) is undefined  \n",
        "- negative numbers → log is not valid  \n",
        "\n",
        "This code checks whether the selected feature (Engine_HP) contains any zero or negative values.\n",
        "\n",
        "### What happened here?\n",
        "\n",
        "- Since **Engine_HP contains only positive values**, it is safe to apply the log transformation.\n",
        "- Therefore, the model uses **log(Engine_HP)** as the predictor.\n",
        "\n",
        "### What if it wasn’t positive?\n",
        "\n",
        "If Engine_HP had zeros or negatives, the code would automatically select another variable that is entirely positive to avoid errors.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why use a log transformation?\n",
        "\n",
        "Using log(Engine_HP) helps:\n",
        "- reduce skewness\n",
        "- model diminishing effects (e.g., going from 100 → 200 HP matters more than 500 → 600 HP)\n",
        "- potentially improve model performance\n",
        "\n",
        "### Conclusion\n",
        "\n",
        "In this case, **Engine_HP was valid for log transformation**, so it was used directly in the linear-log regression model."
