    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# Multiple Regression: Forward and Backward Variable Selection\n",
        "\n",
        "Next, I perform feature selection to identify a stronger set of predictors for MSRP. I use:\n",
        "- **Forward selection**: starts with no predictors and adds the most useful variables one at a time\n",
        "- **Backward selection**: starts with all predictors and removes the least useful ones one at a time\n",
        "\n",
        "I use **p-values from OLS regression** as the selection rule."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "nk6O1CJFkKLt"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Forward Selection Method (Feature Selection)\n",
        "\n",
        "This function performs **forward selection**, a step-by-step process used to choose the most important variables for a regression model.\n",
        "\n",
        "### How the Algorithm Works\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Start with no variables**\n",
        "   - The model begins empty (no predictors).\n",
        "\n",
        "2. **Test each remaining variable one at a time**\n",
        "   - For every variable not yet selected, the function:\n",
        "     - Temporarily adds it to the current model\n",
        "     - Fits a regression model using **OLS (Ordinary Least Squares)**\n",
        "     - Records the **p-value** of that variable\n",
        "\n",
        "3. **Select the best variable**\n",
        "   - The variable with the **lowest p-value** (strongest statistical significance) is chosen.\n",
        "\n",
        "4. **Check significance level**\n",
        "   - If the p-value is **less than 0.05**, the variable is considered statistically significant and is added to the model.\n",
        "   - If not, the process stops.\n",
        "\n",
        "5. **Repeat the process**\n",
        "   - The algorithm continues adding variables one by one until no additional variables improve the model significantly.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Key Concept: p-value\n",
        "\n",
        "- The **p-value** measures whether a variable meaningfully contributes to explaining the target (MSRP).\n",
        "- A smaller p-value (< 0.05) means the variable is statistically important.\n",
        "\n",
        "### What the Code is Doing Internally\n",
        "\n",
        "- `selected_features` → keeps track of variables already chosen  \n",
        "- `remaining_features` → variables still being tested  \n",
        "- For each iteration:\n",
        "  - It builds multiple temporary models\n",
        "  - Compares their p-values\n",
        "  - Picks the best variable to add\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why This is Useful\n",
        "\n",
        "Forward selection helps:\n",
        "- Reduce overfitting by avoiding unnecessary variables\n",
        "- Improve model interpretability\n",
        "- Identify the most important predictors of MSRP\n",
        "\n",
        "### Final Output\n",
        "\n",
        "The function returns a list of selected features that provide the best statistically significant model based on the given threshold (0.05)."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "qMaF2WuCrnXO"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "def forward_selection(X, y, significance_level=0.05):\n",
        "    initial_features = []\n",
        "    remaining_features = list(X.columns)\n",
        "    selected_features = []\n",
        "\n",
        "    while remaining_features:\n",
        "        results = []\n",
        "        for feature in remaining_features:\n",
        "            features_to_test = selected_features + [feature]\n",
        "            X_with_const = sm.add_constant(X[features_to_test])\n",
        "            model = sm.OLS(y, X_with_const).fit()\n",
        "            p_value = model.pvalues[feature]\n",
        "            results.append((feature, p_value))\n",
        "\n",
        "        results.sort(key=lambda x: x[1])\n",
        "        best_feature, best_p = results[0]\n",
        "\n",
        "        if best_p < significance_level:\n",
        "            selected_features.append(best_feature)\n",
        "            remaining_features.remove(best_feature)\n",
        "        else:\n",
        "            break\n",
        "\n",
        "    return selected_features"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "XTNsO_ZRkMbT"
      },
      "execution_count": 28,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "###Backward Elimination Method (Feature Selection)\n",
        "\n",
        "This function performs **backward elimination**, a feature selection technique that starts with all variables and removes the least useful ones step by step.\n",
        "\n",
        "### How the Algorithm Works\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Start with all variables**\n",
        "   - The model initially includes every available predictor.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. **Fit the regression model**\n",
        "   - An OLS (Ordinary Least Squares) regression is run using all current features.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. **Evaluate p-values**\n",
        "   - The function looks at the **p-values** of each variable (excluding the constant).\n",
        "   - The p-value indicates how statistically significant each variable is.\n",
        "\n",
        "4. **Remove the worst variable**\n",
        "   - The variable with the **highest p-value** (least significant) is identified.\n",
        "   - If this p-value is **greater than 0.05**, the variable is removed from the model.\n",
        "\n",
        "5. **Repeat the process**\n",
        "   - The model is re-fit after removing the variable.\n",
        "   - This continues until all remaining variables have p-values less than 0.05.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Key Concept: p-value\n",
        "\n",
        "- A **high p-value (> 0.05)** means the variable does not significantly contribute to predicting MSRP.\n",
        "- A **low p-value (< 0.05)** means the variable is important and should be kept.\n",
        "\n",
        "### What the Code is Doing Internally\n",
        "\n",
        "- `features` → starts with all predictors  \n",
        "- In each loop:\n",
        "  - Builds a regression model\n",
        "  - Finds the least significant variable\n",
        "  - Removes it if it doesn’t meet the threshold\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why This is Useful\n",
        "\n",
        "Backward elimination helps:\n",
        "- Simplify the model by removing unnecessary variables\n",
        "- Improve interpretability\n",
        "- Reduce noise and potential overfitting\n",
        "\n",
        "### Final Output\n",
        "\n",
        "The function returns a list of variables that remain after removing all statistically insignificant predictors. These variables form a more efficient and meaningful regression model."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "3QKGlIvArwjX"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "def backward_elimination(X, y, significance_level=0.05):\n",
        "    features = list(X.columns)\n",
        "\n",
        "    while len(features) > 0:\n",
        "        X_with_const = sm.add_constant(X[features])\n",
        "        model = sm.OLS(y, X_with_const).fit()\n",
        "\n",
        "        p_values = model.pvalues.drop('const')\n",
        "        worst_p = p_values.max()\n",
        "\n",
        "        if worst_p > significance_level:\n",
        "            worst_feature = p_values.idxmax()\n",
        "            features.remove(worst_feature)\n",
        "        else:\n",
        "            break\n",
        "\n",
        "    return features"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "qdG4gEcVkPHa"
      },
      "execution_count": 29,
      "outputs": []
    },
