        "### How to Read This Plot\n",
        "\n",
        "- Each point represents one car in the test dataset  \n",
        "- Ideally, points should lie along a **45-degree diagonal line**, where:\n",
        "  - Predicted value = Actual value  \n",
        "- The closer the points are to this diagonal, the more accurate the model\n",
        "\n",
        "### What This Plot Shows\n",
        "\n",
        "- There is a **general upward trend**, meaning the model captures the overall relationship — higher actual prices tend to have higher predicted prices.\n",
        "- However, the points are **widely scattered**, especially for higher-priced vehicles.\n",
        "- The model appears to:\n",
        "  - **Underestimate very expensive cars** (points far below where they should be)\n",
        "  - Have more variability (error) as MSRP increases\n",
        "\n",
        "### Key Insights\n",
        "\n",
        "- The model performs **reasonably well for lower and mid-range cars**\n",
        "- Performance **decreases for high-end vehicles**, suggesting the model struggles with luxury or extreme values\n",
        "- The spread of points indicates **prediction errors are still significant**\n",
        "\n",
        "### Conclusion\n",
        "\n",
        "While the model captures the general trend in car prices, it lacks precision, especially for expensive vehicles. This suggests that additional features or more advanced modeling techniques may be needed to improve prediction accuracy."
